AGI - &nbsp;Two of the five horses of the British army who yesterday ran off running unchanged in the middle of London and galoppato on the streets at the peak hour are in "gravious conditions", announces the defense minister James Cartlidge. "The horses were five. They were all recovered. Three of them are well, two are unfortunately in relatively serious conditions and of course we will keep under control their conditions," said Sky News Minister. The names of the injured horses are Vida and Quaker, he added. Seven horses and six soldiers of the Household Cavalry were engaged in an exercise in Belgravia, near the regiment barracks near Hyde Park, when chaos broke out on Wednesday morning. Four soldiers were disarcionated by their horses and five of the animals were released, frightened by the cement moved by the builders who hit the ground. Two horses then ran along busy roads, crashing buses, taxis and other traffic.
<div </div
&nbsp;
Three of the disarcionate soldiers were taken to the hospital for investigations, but no one is in danger of life. A number of prestigious army cavalry regiments have stables in the British capital and horses are a regular view around the government buildings of Whitehall, Buckingham Palace, The Mall and near Hyde Park. Cartlidge pointed out that it is "extremely unlikely" that yesterday's events repeat. "You probably know that the army has horses in practice in central London every day of the week. On average, about 150 horses are practicing every day," he said on the LBC radio. "So this scenario is extremely unlikely." The London ambulance service was called at 8:25 (the 9:25 in Italy) for the reporting of a horse thrown person in Buckingham Palace Road.
&nbsp;
Two horses were recovered by the City of London police, which controls the Square Mile financial district. The agents contained two animals while "an army horse box picked up the horses and transported them to veterinary care." A Mercedes driver told the LBC radio he was waiting outside a hotel in Buckingham Palace Road when he heard something hit his car. He said he saw three or four horses near the vehicle and that an army knight had been stunned and wounded. A horse crashed into a two-story bus parked, destroying the windshield.
