AGI - The leader of the United States House of Representatives, Republican Mike Johnson, was criticized during a tense visit to Columbia University, while protests against the Gaza War on U.S. campuses spread. Yesterday, the police broke out among the students who manifested in a Texas university, arresting 34 people, including a photographer of a local warhead, against the background of rising sit-ins and student camps in colleges as part of a growing wave of pro-Palestina events. Johnson reported that Columbia officials lost control of the situation and invited the university director, Nemat Shafik, to resign.
&nbsp;
While the heads of the university are committed to disconnecting campus disorders from one coast to another of the country, some have quickly turned to law enforcement, such as the University of Texas in Austin. Here, hundreds of policemen, including some horse and manganelli, hurled yesterday against the protesters to get them away from the main lawn of the campus, making them at some point fall to the ground. The agents made their way through the crowd to arrest: 34 in total, according to the data of the U.S. Department of Public Security. The police left after hours of effort to bring the crowd under control; About 300 protesters then returned to sit on the grass and sing under the iconic tower of the athene's clock.
<div </div
Students protesting against the war in Gaza ask universities to cut financial ties with Israel and disinvest companies that support the ongoing conflict for over six months. Some Jewish students claim that demonstrations have turned into a wave of anti-Semitism. Even at Columbia, yesterday, law enforcement intervened, in an initiative that led the protesters to ask for the resignation of director Shafik, who yesterday met the President of the House. Johnson then held a press conference on campus, along with other Republican deputies: he rejected the version for which protests fall into freedom of speech and then go protected and denounced that Columbia leaders failed to protect Jewish students among concerns about anti-Semitism within and around the campus.
<div </div
"This is dangerous," Johnson said. "We respect freedom of speech, respect the diversity of ideas, but there is a way to do it legally and it is not what it is." "My message to students within the camp is to return to class and end these nonsense," he added. "We can't listen," the boys yelled at the House Speaker. Johnson also hypothesized the possibility of calling the troops of the National Guard, which the democratic ruler of New York Kathy Hochul said he was not going to do.
